00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:47.490
&gt;&gt; So you were discussing, you know, we have
standards for, you know, soil consistency

00:31:47.490 --> 00:31:51.780
and grape size and you know, ripeness and
things like that. I'm curious how you came

00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:54.860
up with those? You know, as you said, "It's
not like you need a two foot log, you know,

00:31:54.860 --> 00:31:57.770
you need a wine at the end." So, where do
you go about benchmarking for the different

00:31:57.770 --> 00:32:07.620
steps in the process?
&gt;&gt; AHLMANN: I think the best way to answer

00:32:07.620 --> 00:32:18.230
is to pick an example. And, for example, before
we harvest, we run lab results, we take some

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:24.330
grapes that we pick at random across the vineyard
and we want to make sure that they are within

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:29.730
certain parameters. So, there's one measurement
that you do called "Bricks", it's named after

00:32:29.730 --> 00:32:37.410
a professor who invented the—a way to measure
sugar and juice. And you want to make sure

00:32:37.410 --> 00:32:44.760
that you have enough sugar to produce the
alcohol level as an example. So, depending

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:54.920
on the style of wine you want, you say, "Well,
it probably has to be between 24, 23 to 28

00:32:54.920 --> 00:33:01.620
for the heavy Zinfandel, something like that.
So, you know that per grape. But that's not

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:07.730
quite enough because the sugar tells you something
but you also have to make sure that you get

00:33:07.730 --> 00:33:15.150
other things in the—in the final wine. So,
what we will do after we have acidity breaks

00:33:15.150 --> 00:33:21.940
and a couple of other things in the juice,
we will go in and we will at random pick grapes

00:33:21.940 --> 00:33:27.090
from across the vineyard and we will taste
them. And we basically go after two things

00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:35.080
when we do that tasting. We crush the seeds
between our teeth and of course, it have to

00:33:35.080 --> 00:33:39.440
be brown because they're not ripe unless they're
brown, but we also taste them. And if there's

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:44.260
the slightest touch of bitterness, they're
not ready. But you can measure that--well,

00:33:44.260 --> 00:33:50.670
some new things coming out, well, maybe you
can. But, when you try to measure that or

00:33:50.670 --> 00:33:54.930
taste that a couple of times, you know exactly
whether it's right or wrong. So, it's like

00:33:54.930 --> 00:34:01.970
zero, one. The other thing you try to do when
you taste the grapes at the end is to crush

00:34:01.970 --> 00:34:08.250
the skin and see if there's any flavors coming
out of that because that flavor that translates

00:34:08.250 --> 00:34:16.590
to the wine is the last thing that happens
with the grapes before you pick them. When

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:21.649
it comes to the soils, they're very exact--I
mentioned boron is something you don't want

00:34:21.649 --> 00:34:29.230
and there's a very exact limits for when it
starts to damage the wine. And my son is sitting

00:34:29.230 --> 00:34:33.339
down there; he could probably answer this
better because he is into the vidiculture

00:34:33.339 --> 00:34:39.629
side of it. But if you, for example, in an
area have too much or too little magnesium,

00:34:39.629 --> 00:34:44.190
not within where you want to be, you can just--if
you fly up in a helicopter and look down at

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:50.230
the vineyard, you can see it. It just affects
the growth that much. Was that a good enough

00:34:50.230 --> 00:34:57.609
answer, son? Okay, I passed.
